Africa's religious divide between Christianity and Islam stems from historical expansion. Islam spread through Arab conquests and trade from the 7th century, reaching North, West, and East Africa. Christianity arrived in North Africa in the 1st century and expanded significantly during European colonialism, especially in Sub-Saharan Africa. This created a predominantly Muslim North and a largely Christian South, with a ‚Äúreligious fault line‚Äù in countries like Nigeria and Sudan, often leading to tensions.

Traditional African religions remain influential, especially in rural areas, emphasizing ancestor worship, animism, and nature-based spirituality. Minor religions like Hinduism, Buddhism, and Judaism exist due to migration and trade, while syncretism blends traditional beliefs with Christianity and Islam.

The Middle East and the Americas have an obesity problem.

Countries with high obesity rates often face a mix of dietary, lifestyle, and socio-economic factors. Rapid urbanization and increased income can lead to a diet high in calories, processed foods, and sugars, while a more sedentary lifestyle reduces physical activity. 

In many Middle Eastern nations, the shift from traditional diets to more Westernized, energy-dense foods‚Äîcoupled with less active lifestyles‚Äîhas contributed significantly to rising obesity levels. Similarly, in the Americas, widespread fast-food culture, urban living, and economic factors also drive high obesity rates.
